1. Create a text layer with the sentence you want to manipulate and animate.

2. Click on the text layer to select it, then add a text animator for the property you want to change (e.g., Position, Opacity, Scale, etc.). Go to the menu bar and choose `Animation` > `Animate text` > `Position`.

3. Rename the Animator (e.g., "Animator 1") to something like "Word Animator" for clarity.

4. With the Animator selected, choose `Add` > `Selector` > `Expression Selector`.

5. Create a Controller layer (a Null Object). Go to `Layer` > `New` > `Null Object`. With the Null Object layer selected, apply a Slider Control to it by going to `Effect` > `Expression Controls` > `Slider Control`. Rename the Slider Control to "Word Index."

6. Go back to your text layer's "Word Animator" and twirl down until you see the "Expression Selector." Alt-click (Option-click for Mac) on the stopwatch icon next to the "Amount."

7. Enter the following expression for the Amount:

```javascript
var slider = thisComp.layer("Null 1").effect("Word Index")("Slider");  // Point to the slider control
var wordIndex = Math.round(slider) - 1;  // Convert slider value to index (subtracting one since indexing starts at 0)
var text = thisLayer.text.sourceText.value;  // Get the text content from the layer
var words = text.split(/\b\s/);  // Split the text into an array based on word boundaries followed by space
var currentWord = words[wordIndex];  // Get the word at the current index

// Initialize the start and end index of the characters range
var result = 0;
if (wordIndex >= 0 && wordIndex < words.length) {
    var totalLength = 0;
    // Calculate total length of characters before the desired word
    for (var i = 0; i < wordIndex; i++) {
        totalLength += words[i].length + 1;  // Add 1 for the space
    }
    // Now map these indices to calculate the range of the word for selection
    if (textIndex >= totalLength && textIndex < totalLength + currentWord.length) {
        result = 100;
    }
}
result;
```

8. Make sure to change `"Null 1"` to the name of your actual Null Object if you have a different name for it.

9. When you adjust the Slider Control, it should now control the animator based on the word index, selecting each word in sequence.

The updated expression splits the text into words using the JavaScript split method and applies the specified animation property to the word that corresponds to the index number derived from the slider's value.

The expression also accounts for the zero-based indexing of JavaScript arrays by subtracting 1 from the slider value. Keep in mind that this expression will match whole words followed by spaces, so if your text has punctuation, you might need to adjust the regex in the split function accordingly.

To hide all words except for the selected one using the Word Index Slider, we can set up a text animator for the opacity property. Then, we'll create an expression that uses an Expression Selector to control the opacity of each word based on the slider value. Here's a step-by-step guide to achieve this:

1. **Create a Text Layer**: Type your sentence into a new text layer.

2. **Add an Opacity Animator**: Click on the text layer to select it, then go to the menu bar and choose **Animation > Animate Text > Opacity**. Set the opacity value of this animator to 0% to hide the text by default.

3. **Rename the Animator**: If needed, rename the Animator (e.g., "Animator 1") to "Word Opacity" for clarity.

4. **Create a Slider Control**: Go to **Layer > New > Null Object** to create a null object (if you haven't already). With the null object selected, go to **Effect > Expression Controls > Slider Control**. Rename the Slider Control to "Word Index."

5. **Add an Expression Selector**: On your text layer, under the "Word Opacity" animator, find the existing "Range Selector". Click the "Add" button next to the "Range Selector" and choose "Selector" > "Expression Selector".

6. **Write the Expression**: Alt-click the stopwatch icon next to "**Amount**" in the "Expression Selector" you just added. Enter the following expression:

```javascript
var sliderVal = Math.round(thisComp.layer("Null 1").effect("Word Index")("Slider"));
var textLayer = thisLayer;
var words = textLayer.text.sourceText.value.split(/\s+/);
var totalChars = 0;
var currentWordIndex = 0;
var match = false;

for (var i = 0; i < words.length; i++) {
    if (currentWordIndex === sliderVal - 1) {
        var wordLength = words[i].length;
        if (textIndex >= totalChars && textIndex < totalChars + wordLength) {
            match = true;
        }
    }
    totalChars += words[i].length + 1; // Include space or punctuation
    currentWordIndex++;
}

match ? 100 : 0;
```

7. **Test the Slider**: Adjust the slider control on the null object, which should now result in only the word corresponding to the slider's index being visible, while hiding the rest of the words in the text layer.

Make sure to replace `"Null 1"` with the actual name of your null object if it's different. The expression calculates the range of each word and makes the word at the slider index fully opaque (100) and the rest of the words fully transparent (0).

This approach assumes that words are separated by spaces only. If there is punctuation, you may need to account for that when splitting the text into words by adjusting the regular expression in the `split` method.

In After Effects expressions, you can use the `linear()` function to map a range of values from one domain to another, effectively remapping the values of a control slider. This is often used to translate the value of a slider from its native range to a range that matches the application in your animation or effect.

Here's a basic example of mapping a Slider Control with a value range of 0 to 100 to an opacity property with a range of 0% to 100%:

```javascript
// Getting the slider value
var slider = thisComp.layer("Null 1").effect("Slider Control")("Slider");

// Mapping the slider's range to a new range
// linear(value, inputMin, inputMax, outputMin, outputMax);
var mappedOpacity = linear(slider, 0, 100, 0, 100);

// Set the opacity
mappedOpacity;
```

In this example, `linear()` takes five arguments:

- `value`: The current value of the input (from your slider).
- `inputMin`: The minimum value of your slider's expected range.
- `inputMax`: The maximum value of your slider's expected range.
- `outputMin`: The minimum of the destination range (e.g., the opacity could range from 0 to 100).
- `outputMax`: The maximum of the destination range.

Now let's say you want to reverse the direction of the slider, so that as it goes from 0 to 100, the opacity goes from 100% to 0%. You simply switch the output range:

```javascript
var reversedOpacity = linear(slider, 0, 100, 100, 0);

reversedOpacity;
```

For more complex mapping where the relationship is not linear, you might find the `ease()` function useful, where values accelerate or decelerate between ranges:

```javascript
var easedOpacity = ease(slider, 0, 100, 100, 0);

easedOpacity;
```

Adjust the `inputMin`, `inputMax`, `outputMin`, and `outputMax` values to correspond to the desired ranges for your project's specific requirements. This simple mapping technique can be incredibly powerful in After Effects for creating complex animations controlled by intuitive slider movements.

In After Effects scripting, you cannot directly get the size of a text layer as you would in expressions with sourceRectAtTime. Instead, you need to calculate the size based on the properties of the text layer that are available through scripting, such as font size, tracking, and the actual text content. However, keep in mind that the exact bounds of the rendered text are not accessible through the scripting API as of the Knowledge Cutoff date in 2023.

Here's an example of how you might approach calculating an approximate width of a text layer using scripting:

```javascript
var textLayer = app.project.activeItem.layer("Your Text Layer Name");
var textDocument = textLayer.property("Source Text").value;

// Get basic text properties
var fontSize = textDocument.fontSize;
var text = textDocument.text;
var tracking = textDocument.tracking;

// Approximate the width of the text
// Note: This is a rough estimation and may not be accurate for all fonts and styles
var approxWidth = text.length * (fontSize + (tracking / 1000 * fontSize));

// Return the approximate width
approxWidth;
```

The above is a simplification and does not take into account line breaks, different character widths (since it assumes monospaced font), style changes, or transformations applied to the layer itself, such as scaling. This will give you a very rough approximation that might work for simple cases where precision is not key.

If you need the exact bounding box of the text layer, the recommended approach, as of the last update to After Effects scripting capabilities, is to use expressions within the After Effects UI.

Here's how you might do it with an expression:

```javascript
var textProp = thisLayer.sourceText;
var textDocument = textProp.value;
var box = thisLayer.sourceRectAtTime(time, false);
[box.width, box.height]
```

You can then use script-to-expression communication to pass these values back to your script. Store the expression's results in a source that the script can read, like the text of a different layer or the value of an expression control.

In a future update to After Effects, the scripting API may include native functions for getting the bounds of text layers directly, but until then, we need to use workarounds as demonstrated here.

In After Effects, if you are writing a script (as opposed to an expression) and you need to calculate the approximate width and height of a text layer's content, you can't directly get the pixel dimensions such as from the `sourceRectAtTime()` function, which is available only in expressions.

You would typically resort to manually measuring or approximating text based on known properties like font size, but this would still be quite a coarse estimation due to the complexities of different font metrics, tracking, leading, and text box dimensions.

If you absolutely need to get the width and height of a text layer in a script, one workaround involves creating an expression, evaluating it, and then reading the results.

Below is an example of how you might attempt this:

1. Create an expression on a property of a layer that includes the `sourceRectAtTime()` function, which gives you the size and position of the text box.

```javascript
// Add this expression to a property (for example, the position of a null object)
var box = thisComp.layer("Your Text Layer Name").sourceRectAtTime(time, false);
[box.width, box.height]
```

2. Use a script to apply the expression to a property, read out the value, and then remove the expression if necessary.

Here's an example script:

```javascript
// Apply an expression to a property and get the value
var comp = app.project.activeItem;
var textLayer = comp.layer("Your Text Layer Name");
var controlLayer = comp.layers.addNull(); // Create a control layer
var controlProperty = controlLayer.position; // Use position as an example

// Set up and apply the expression
var expr = "var box = thisComp.layer(\"" + textLayer.name + "\").sourceRectAtTime(time, false); [box.width, box.height]";
controlProperty.expression = expr;

// After Effects must do a screen refresh in order for the expression to be applied and give a result
app.executeCommand(app.findMenuCommandId("Refresh Frame"));

var width = controlProperty.value[0];
var height = controlProperty.value[1];

// Do something with the width and height here

alert("Text Width: " + width + "\nText Height: " + height); // Example action showing the result

// Remove the expression if it's no longer needed
controlProperty.expression = "";

// Optional: Remove the control layer if it was only needed for this calculation
controlLayer.remove();
```

This script essentially creates an expression temporarily to measure the text layer size and retrieves those values. Be cautious with this method, and take into account that it might not work correctly if the text has animation applied or if the comp isn't properly refreshed.

Please remember that as of my knowledge cutoff date, precise script-based retrieval of text size is not as straightforward as in expressions, and this is a workaround. Future versions of After Effects might include better support for this feature in scripting.

If you want to use an After Effects expression to get the size of text from a parent text layer, you can use the `sourceRectAtTime()` function to get the bounding box dimensions of the text element. This method provides the width, height, top, left, bottom, and right properties of the box surrounding the text.

Here's a simple expression to get the width and height of a parent text layer's bounding box:

```javascript
// Assuming this expression is placed on a child layer and you want to get the size of a parent text layer.
var parentTextLayer = thisComp.layer("Parent Text Layer Name");
var parentTextSize = parentTextLayer.sourceRectAtTime(time, false);
var width = parentTextSize.width;
var height = parentTextSize.height;

// Output the width and height as an array, or use them as needed
[width, height]
```

You'd replace `"Parent Text Layer Name"` with the actual name of the parent text layer from which you want to retrieve the size.

Please note that `sourceRectAtTime()` considers the visible content of the layer. If you have transformations or animations on your text layer, make sure you evaluate the `sourceRectAtTime()` at the correct time, usually by using `time`, which refers to the current composition time.

If you wish to align or position the child layer with respect to the text size of the parent layer, you can use the `left`, `top`, `width`, and `height` properties of the `sourceRectAtTime()` return object to calculate the desired position or transformation. Here's an example of centering a shape layer based on the parent text layer's dimensions:

```javascript
var parentTextLayer = thisComp.layer("Parent Text Layer Name");
var textRect = parentTextLayer.sourceRectAtTime(time, false);
var textWidth = textRect.width;
var textHeight = textRect.height;
var textLeft = textRect.left;
var textTop = textRect.top;

// Calculate the center of the text bounding box relative to the layer's anchor point
var centerX = textLeft + textWidth / 2;
var centerY = textTop + textHeight / 2;

// Apply this center position to the shape layer's anchor point for centering
var shapeLayer = thisLayer;
shapeLayer.anchorPoint.setValue([centerX, centerY]);
```

This script positions the shape layer so that its anchor point is at the center of the parent text layer's content. Adjust the script as necessary if you want different types of alignment (e.g., top-left, bottom-right, etc.).

